{{italic title}} '''''Rapid Interpretation of EKG's''''' is a best-selling textbook for over 30 years<ref name = Sullivan>{{cite journal | last = Sullivan | first = Patrick | title = Book Review: Rapid Interpretation of EKG's, 6th edition. | journal = Canadian Journal of Anesthesia | volume = 48 | page = 1050 | year = 2001 | doi = 10.1007/bf03016605}}</ref> that teaches the basics of interpreting [[electrocardiogram]]s. It adopts a simplistic fill-in-the-blank style<ref>{{cite book | last = Dubin | first = Dale | title = Rapid Interpretation of EKG's | publisher = Cover Publishing | location = Tampa, FL | edition = 6th | year = 2000 | ISBN = 0-912912-06-5}}</ref> and is suited for medical students and junior residents.<ref name = Sullivan /> The book was written by [[Dale Dubin]], [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]], a [[plastic surgery|plastic surgeon]] and convicted felon,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/news/2001/dec/07/fine-print-redux-beneficent-doctor-made-child/ |title=Fine print redux: beneficent doctor made child pornos |author= |date=7 December 2001 |work=Yale Daily News |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=11 April 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130209202658/http://www.yaledailynews.com/news/2001/dec/07/fine-print-redux-beneficent-doctor-made-child/ |archivedate=9 February 2013 |df= }}</ref> who has written several books on [[cardiology]] including ''Ion Adventure in the Heartland: Exploring the Heart's Ionic-Molecular Microcosm''<ref>{{cite book | last = Dubin | first = Dale | title = Ion Adventure in the Heartland: Exploring the Heart's Ionic-Molecular Microcosm | publisher = Cover Publishing Company | year = 2003 | ISBN = 9780912912110}}</ref> and ''Understanding Cardio-pulmonary Resuscitation''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Dubin | first = Dale | title = Understanding Cardio-pulmonary Resuscitation | publisher = C.P.R. Inc. | year = 1972}}</ref>
The large yellow book was originally published in 1972; the sixth and most recent edition was published in 2000. In the fiftieth printing, the author hid within the [[copyright notice]] an offer to give his prized 1965 [[Ford Thunderbird]] (which was featured in several photographs in the book) to anyone who actually read the message and responded. Out of 60,000 copies in that printing, only 5 readers noticed and responded, and Dubin's own daughter delivered the car to the winner, a [[Yale School of Medicine|Yale]] medical student, as selected by a random drawing.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Caroline |last=Massad |title=Read the fine print: Student wins T-bird |publisher=Yale Daily News |url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2001/12/05/read-the-fine-print-student-wins-t-bird|date= December 5, 2001 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Yale puts distance on car contest |publisher=Hartford Courant |date= December 2001 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/93742038.html?dids=93742038:93742038&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Dec+06%2C+2001&author=JANICE+D%27ARCY%3B+Courant+Staff+Writer&pub=Hartford+Courant&desc=YALE+PUTS+DISTANCE+ON+CAR+CONTEST&pqatl=google |first=Janice |last=D'Arcy }}</ref>
